data.title: Realist painter Lucian Freud, famed for his nudes of family and friends, dies aged 88
data.meta_description: In recent years, his paintings commanded staggering prices at auction, including one of an overweight nude woman sleeping on a couch that sold in 2008 for £17.2m.
data.text:
Realist painter Lucian Freud has died aged 88 after a brief illness

Lucian Freud, a towering and uncompromising figure in the art world for more than 50 years, has died, his New York-based art dealer said. He was 88.

Spokeswoman Bettina Prentice said that Freud died after an illness at his London home late on Wednesday night, but didn't give any further details.

Freud was known for his intense realist portraits, particularly of nudes.

In recent years his paintings commanded staggering prices at auction, including one of an overweight nude woman sleeping on a couch that sold in 2008 for £17.2million.

William R. Acquavella, his dealer, said in a statement that he would mourn Freud 'as one of the great painters of the twentieth century'.

'He lived to paint and painted until the day he died, far removed from the noise of the art world,' he said.

Freud stubbornly refused to follow the trends of that world, insisting on using his realist approach even when it was out of favour with critics and collectors.

He developed his own unique style, eventually winning recognition as one of the world's greatest painters.

'He certainly is considered one of the most important painters of the 20th and 21st Centuries,' said Brett Gorvy, deputy chairman of the postwar art department at Christie's auction house in New York.

'He stayed with his figurative approach even when it was extremely unpopular, when abstraction was the leading concept, and as time moved on his classic approach has proven to be very important.

'He fought the system and basically won.'

Lucian Freud's portrait, Benefits Supervisor Sleeping, sold for a record £17million

He said Freud remained totally dedicated to his work, overcoming all obstacles and painting long hours every day well into his late 80s in a sustained bid to complete his life's work before death overtook him.

'He lived and breathed his art,' said Gorvy. 'For someone who was so successful, he was extraordinarily regulated in his day, with three main sittings a day and some at night. He worked each and every day to this very tough regime.

'He was very aware of his own mortality and he knew his time was very, very precious.'

Freud was the grandson of Sigmund Freud, a leading pioneer of modern psychoanalysis. He was born in Berlin in 1922 and moved to London with his parents Ernst and Lucie Freud in 1933 after Hitler and the Nazis rose to power in Germany.

Freud with Kate Moss at Jude Law and Sadie Frost's son Rudy's first birthday party

He was naturalised as a British subject six years later and spent almost his entire working life based in London, where he was often seen at fashionable restaurants, sometimes with beautiful younger women, including the fashion model Kate Moss, who he painted nude, and other luminaries.

He was at the height of his fame in the last decades of his life, when he still continued to paint for long hours at his studio in London's exclusive Holland Park.

He was even named one of Britain's best dressed men by the fashion magazine GQ when he was well into his ninth decade. But there was little beautiful or sexy in Freud's nude portraits, which did not gloss over a subject's flaws.'

The intimate detail of his paintings sometimes left viewers uncomfortable. 'He has certainly divided critics,' said Starr Figura, a curator at the Museum of Modern Art in New York.

'The ones who don't appreciate him find his work hard to look at and a bit out of step with what is going on in the rest of the world. They have a hard time categorising it.'

She said Freud's work can be unsettling. 'I think his work is very charged, and it is quite disturbing to look at,' she said.

'That's what gives people a problem and that's what gives his work power and fascination.

'His work is incredibly personal, and that comes through. On the other hand it is also very detached and critical and that is what makes it so intense.'

Among his most famous subjects was Queen Elizabeth II, who posed for Freud fully clothed after extensive negotiations between the palace and the painter. The colourful portrait, which the artist donated to the queen's collection, remains one of the most unusual and controversial depictions of the British monarch.

'It makes her look like one of the royal corgis who has suffered a stroke,' said Robin Simon, editor of the British Art Journal. Other critics said more enthusiastically that the work had broken the staid mold of royal portraiture.

Girl with a white dog: This 1951 picture shows the artist's first wife, Kitty Garman, when she was pregnant

Freud shakes hands with The Queen at Buckingham Palace before receiving the Order of Merit - one of Britain's most prestigious chivalry honours

In his studio, Freud worked extremely slowly and deliberately. People who posed for Freud said it sometimes took him months or years to complete a portrait because of his attention to every tiny detail and the complex nature of his brushwork, which gave his paintings a lifelike intensity.

He sometimes spent entire days mixing paints without putting a brush to canvas. When he did finally paint, he would wipe his brush on a cloth rag after every stroke.

Great piles of rags lay on the floor of his studio and eventually he began to incorporate the rags into some of his paintings.

Freud often painted his friends, relatives and fellow artists. Others were simply ordinary people who received a small daily fee for posing for Freud.

He usually refrained from using professional models because he felt they brought artifice into his studio. His 1950-51 portrait of his first wife was to remain one of his most famous and best loved works. The detail of her features, the shadows in the room and her partial nudity are typical of the nuance and frankness of much of Freud's work.

Freud pictured out and about in London

Nudity became a central feature of Freud's art. Painting people without their clothes, he believed, peeled away their outer layer and helped reveal their instincts and desires.

'I'm really interested in people as animals,' he told curators at the Tate Britain museum in advance of a major show in 2002.

'Part of my liking to work from them naked is for that reason, because I can see more ... I like people to look as natural and as physically at ease as animals.'

His first solo exhibition was at the Lefevre Gallery in 1944 after a brief stint working on a merchant ship during World War II.

After the war, Freud left London for several years to paint primarily in France and Greece. On his return in 1948, he started showing his work regularly at various exhibits and also taught art at several schools.

His first major retrospective exhibition appeared at London's Hayward Gallery in 1974 to critical acclaim. Further retrospectives appeared in Paris, Berlin and Washington between 1987-88 and in 2002 at London's Tate Britain museum.

Freud's work can be found in major public collections around the world, including the Tate Gallery and the National Portrait Gallery in London, the National Gallery of Modern Art in Paris and the Museum of Modern Art in New York.

In 1998, prominent art critic Robert Hughes described Freud as 'the greatest living realist painter'. Despite the accolades, he kept trying to improve his work even as the end of his life neared.

'I think the most dangerous thing for an ar'tist would be to be pleased with one's work simply because it is one's own,' he once said. 'One wants every picture to be better than its predecessors. Otherwise, what's the point?'

The painter feuded for many years with his late brother Clement Freud, a popular writer and broadcaster who died in April, 2009. He did not attend Clement Freud's funeral.

Freud's marriage to Kathleen Garman lasted four years and was dissolved in 1952. They had two daughters together. His second marriage, to Caroline Blackwood in 1953, ended in 1957.

Prentice, the spokeswoman, said in an email that funeral arrangements had not yet been made public.

A GENIUS WHOSE LIFE WAS ALWAYS AS DRAMATIC AS HIS ART

BY CHRISTOPHER HUDSON

Lucian Freud, who died last night aged 88 at his London home after a brief illness, was one of the finest British artists of the post-war era, on a par with Henry Moore and Francis Bacon.

For every art critic who mocked Freud’s pallid, fleshy nudes lying in gloomy attic rooms, and derided his unflattering portrait of the Queen, there were a dozen more who declared he was the greatest realist painter of the human figure in their lifetimes.

‘He lived to paint and painted until the day he died, far removed from the noise of the art world,’ William Acquavella, his New York dealer, said last night.

Freud’s paintings sold for millions at auction — just last month, his portrait entitled Woman Smiling fetched nearly £4.8 million when it went under the hammer in London.

As for the wider public, Freud fulfilled their expectations of how a great painter should behave. He lived the part of the bohemian artist to the full: carousing, gambling, and siring large numbers of illegitimate offspring by his countless sexual conquests, alongside the nine children he publicly acknowledged.

He was not an easy man to know. The art critic Brian Sewell described him as ‘aggressive, sour and unfriendly’. He fell out with most of his old friends, and had been estranged for more than 30 years from his brother Sir Clement Freud, the one-time Liberal MP and radio personality, who died two years ago.

The brothers’ rift dated back to their North London childhood when they had a bet about which of them would win a race to Green Park. Clement was leading until Lucian shouted: ‘Stop, thief! He’s stolen my money’ — whereupon Clement was seized by passers-by and Lucian ran on to win.

Lucian Freud's painting of his daughter Bella. He often painted nudes of his friends and family

Lucian Freud was born in 1922 in Berlin, where his father had an architectural practice. His grandfather, the great Sigmund Freud, used to visit Berlin to be treated for his jaw cancer, and one of Lucian’s earliest memories was of Sigmund taking out his false teeth and snapping them at him. But he also awakened his grandson’s interest in art by giving him beautifully illustrated books such as The Arabian Nights.

The Freuds were Jews, though non-practising, and when Hitler came to power in 1933 they left Germany and settled in London.

The Nazis confiscated their German property; three of Lucian’s great-aunts who stayed behind were arrested and sent to Auschwitz, where they died. Freud was deeply affected by the 1945 newsreels of the Nazi extermination camps after they were liberated. They haunted his imagination and fed into the unflinching rawness of his painting.

He was expelled from Dartington Hall in Devon, and then from Bryanston School, where he was asked to leave after dropping his trousers in public in Bournemouth for a bet; (even so, in 1993 he recorded receiving the Order of Merit — one of Britain’s highest honours — in the Bryanston old boys’ newsletter).

Freud pictured in London aged 79, with his muse Emily Bearn

After one term at the Central School of Arts and Crafts in London, he switched to an art school in East Anglia, on the recommendation of a girl he met in a coffee bar.

In 1941, aged 19, he decided to join the Navy, and signed on as an ordinary seaman on an Atlantic convoy to Nova Scotia. Ships in the convoy were attacked and blown up by German U-boats. Freud survived, but was invalided out of the Navy in a state of shock after seeing the dismembered bodies of crewmates hurled through the air.

He stayed in his parents’ house in St John’s Wood, studied briefly at Goldsmiths College and then began teaching at the Slade School of Art.

Still in his 20s, his spiky drawings were becoming admired by a small coterie of important collectors such as the Duke of Devonshire and Sir David Eccles, then the Minister for Works. At night, in the blackout, he used to hang out with artists in Soho and Fitzrovia, wearing a fez and carrying a pet hawk on his wrist in the Tube. His first one-man show, in 1944, brought him public recognition. By this time he had fallen in love for the first time, with a woman 11 years his senior.

Lorna Wishart, tall and feline with enormous deep blue eyes, had been living with the writer Laurie Lee, who wrote of Freud: ‘This mad, unpleasant youth appeals to a sort of craving she has for corruption.’

Freud painted her in Girl With Daffodil, and when she left him in 1945 to return to her husband, she gave him a stuffed zebra’s head.

Lorna introduced him to the family of the celebrated sculptor Jacob Epstein, whose daughter Kitty he would later marry. The delightful writer and woman-about-town Joan Wyndham (briefly Henry Moore’s war-time mistress) had been living with Freud for the previous eight months.

She had fallen in love with his strangeness and saturnine beauty, but was less impressed by his enjoyment of the power he had over women. He moved Kitty into his home while Joan was still mistress of it — the first time she saw her rival was when Kitty entered their bedroom to give Freud a morning cup of tea. Kitty slept on the sofa at first. When Joan was moved to the sofa, she decided it was time to go.

Freud told Joan he was scared of serious relationships. To another ex-lover he confessed he lost interest in a woman when he began to love and respect them, because then they started reminding him of his mother.

Joan Wyndham simply believed that Freud expended most of his emotional energy on his work. ‘He would talk only about himself and his art,’ she said. ‘In eight months I can’t remember him ever asking me one intimate question about myself.’

After Joan left, he lived with Kitty for four years, in a house in Paddington overlooking the Grand Union Canal. She modelled for him during the day, and in the evening they ate out at Soho restaurants. They had two children, Annie and Annabel. But Freud was rapidly being claimed by high society.

Kindred spirits: Freud (left) with another post-war great, the artist Francis Bacon, in the latter's studio in 1953, an era in which the pair spent a lot of time drinking together in Soho

In 1953, he met Caroline Blackwood, the women who would become his next wife. The daughter of a Marquess and descended from Charles II, she was clever and talented — and since her mother was a scion of the Guinness family, the new Mrs Freud and her husband could afford a year’s honeymoon in Paris, a Georgian townhouse in London, a second house in the country and a horse for Lucian to ride at weekends.

Freud painted, drank, gambled and hung out in Soho. His driving was so bad that a magistrate told him to see a psychiatrist; a friend once threw himself out of a Bentley rather than continue with Freud at the wheel.

The marriage burned itself out after three years, by which time Caroline’s drinking habit had established itself. Freud went on to live with a former student of his, the artist Suzy Boyt, by whom he had five children, and then with a teacher, Bernardine Coverley, in a relationship which produced two more children — novelist Esther Freud and fashion designer Bella.

His early paintings redefined British art and his later works stand comparison with the great figurative painters of any period

His prickly temper meant that his relations with men were less forgiving. He fell out with Francis Bacon, whom he met in 1944 and who became an inspiration as well as a friend, over a silly argument about accepting honours from the state (something Bacon refused to do).

Meanwhile, Freud was becoming the most sought-after portrait painter of his day. He turned down requests to paint Pope John Paul II and Diana, Princess of Wales, and politely rejected a suggestion by Prince Charles to donate a picture in return for one of HRH’s watercolours — but he was happy to paint a naked Jerry Hall, eight months pregnant.

He guarded his privacy ferociously. Known as ‘the Hermit of Holland Park’, he rarely gave interviews, and emerged only occasionally to attend smart private parties or to eat in his favourite Notting Hill restaurants.

In 2001, at the age of 79, Freud set up house with a woman 52 years his junior. Emily Bearn, a young journalist, was probably the last in the long line of models who became his mistress. Like the others, she felt privileged by his attention, however short-lived, because she was able to spend time with one of the truly great artists of our age.

Lucien Freud with his daughter, fashion designer Bella Freud, pictured in 2008

The seal was set upon his pre-eminence by the major retrospective of his work, the largest ever mounted, at Tate Britain in 2002. It proved that painting was not a dead art form, and would never be displaced by photography so long as an artist with his intensity and singularity of vision survives.

His canvases have the capacity to shock — Freud once announced ‘a painting should at best outrage your sensibilities’. But his unsparing, unsentimental eye was able to find a vulnerable beauty in lumpish naked flesh which few artists since Rembrandt have expressed so well.

As Sir Nicholas Serota, director of the Tate, said last night: ‘The vitality of his nudes, the intensity of the still-life paintings and the presence of his portraits of family and friends guarantee Freud a unique place in the pantheon of late 20th-century art.

‘His early paintings redefined British art and his later works stand comparison with the great figurative painters of any period.’
